lislon- hut now ho\nHi-vi' that th. W. nl.ls io!:i is con\ntmllrd hv o it a iti i ial in' I'rst and\nthai for this n-asnn aloii'- I In- Now\nYork lli''sM.i'! i!l\nto Mr Tall tln'ti tin'\nItn'lf to hl.iinc lor\nKtvo Its Sll:Olt\nWin Id has only\nIts iitii'tivlahh'\nI'oor old Nnu York World' It lias\nkotiip widl luirin d mailt marks. Hill\nnow thill It has I ii iiiiiiiaski'd rvrn\nllif Kood It has ilmu' In inrtaln pur\nlii'ulaiH do's not sirvo to irotict It\nfrom the ilhi's of nuui of all jiartlrH\nho di-Hdsi Iiyporrisy evrti though\nttioy pity th liyiiM'ilti'.\nTHE LEADER VS. THE BOSS.\nTh.- Inailnr is not a limn who thinks\nfor tlm h'oi1i'. hut tho nuin who\nIhtnliH with tlm ii'odi' Tim Inadnr Ih\nKoitiK In the same dlrni'tlon Ihat t In\nl'odi' an' hoIiii: far 'iintmli ahnad to\nI'm in advain'o hut not far I'limmh to\nl)n out of slu'hl Thi' lomli'r Is not\nunly in H.vmiuiihy with tlm n'opli', lull\nt;t milt's upon piTtoiaNlou to Infill\nfnrn thi'tu Ho pri'si'titH his arcu\nIWMits to tln'in. hut ri'i'oKiilzi'H tlm\nrirh' of th\" pi oplo to r'i'Ct tiny prop\n(m.lloii Hiilin.itii'd hy lilni Thn load\nI'r'g title to h'iiili'1 ship tests upon tils\nnlilllty to pioposn the lent thlnK at\ndh\" rlyhl lime and. an IhoHe who fol\nlow the leader follow lilin volun\ntarily, he luiiiit appeal to their con\nI'lenen and their JudKtneiit. The\nleader a niolder of opinion, and a\ntimldnr of opinion does not create pub\nlie opinion- he merely enpretmeii It In\neffective InncunKH. As Thomas .lef\nfurson almply put Into appropriate\nwords the asplrntlona of the people,\nan, to-day, the leader the niolder of\npublic opinion colim Into current lan\nuiiK\" the Rentlnient, like precloiiB\nmetal, which experience brings forth\nfrom himiaiilty'a ttreut storn houae,\nHie bon, however. Is an entirely\nrtlffi'tent charactei If the word \"char,\nac-lnr\" can be applied to one who Is\nnfiin without character. The boss\nh.is no Bvnipathy with the people; he\nh.ns his own Intercuts to serve, and\nwhatever authority he enn secure he\nturns to his own private aihanuiKe.\nTVe boss Is an embezzler of power,\nami. measured by every moral stand\naril, he is In the same criminal clnss\nwi'h the embezzler of money. The\nlirew lias Introduced bribery, corrup\ntion and Intimldntlon into jiolltlcs and\nln will K out when these arR elim\ninated \"l.et the people rule\" la as\nti'iieh a terror to the boss iu the com\nD'.mdment \"Thou shnlt not steal,\" Is\nto ilie thief. The spread of the pri\nmary Is only a renctlon from boss rule,\nami, like every other plan for the\nbrinfflnK of Koverniuetit nearer to the\np.tipln, the primary system Increases\ntbw relative Influence of the real lead\ner and lessens the Inlluenre of the\nfc 8H.\nA WORD AS TO COWARDS.\nKi-Conjtreasman Minefield of Maine\nla quoted aa aaylnK that \"oonKrosa\nwn are the most cowardly aet on\nearth,\" and that they aro \"afraid to\nact In any manner which could preju\nakrm their re-elpctlon.\" Ho admits\nbwt there la a seeming reluctance In\nttr that \"the people should control\nths fOTernment,\" thouKh he adds:\n\"But tecauae of this cowardice of leu\nleViitora I doubt If direct election of\na natora would Improve conditions.\nXI senate would then be in a like po\nWUcm to members of the lower body.\"\nT dlapatch concludes: \"Mr. Lit\ntWUeld deprecated the branding of all\nxctt men as malefactors and said ha\nfceilercd the amassing of great wealth\nia of considerable benefit to the coun-\ntry If rlKhtly a lrnlnlRtered.\" It was\ntint nnccspary for .Mi l.lttlefleld to !.iy\nthis In order to iliscim.' a!s point of\nview. No one brands \"all rich rn'ri\nas niiilefacior.s,\" and tho\"i' who hei-.u\ntheir defense of piedato:y wealth with\nthe assumption thai nil rich nun are\nnttackecl are either ih ivlvcd th\"tn\nselves or are tryini; to dendve\nothers.\nHut what about Mr. Mttlefleld s at\ntack on coiiKressm\"!!'.' Aro they all\ncowards because they rip afraid to\nact contrary to tho wiihes of llieir\nconstituents? And are senators brave\nbecause they defy the wishua of their\nconstituents?\nSenators wh.i defy their constitu\nents do so not from a hlKh sense of\nduty, but buratise they are servile\nrepresentatives of great corporations\nthat hide In the darkness and con\ntrol the government through the ofll\ncla! whom they raise to power.\nMr. l.lttlefleld was not always thus\nIti'ii he went to congress he was\nsoinethliig of a reformer hlmsidf. lie\nIntroduced an antitrust bill It was\nsaid to be an admiiils'iutlon ii'.'iis\niite It pas.-d ihe house by an al\nmost unanimous vote, hut It died In\nthe sena'e. The \"bravo\" siiia'o:s\nkilled It. after tin- \"lowaidly\" mom\nl.\"ts of i he liou-.e hud passed It? Was\nIt a good bill? If so. what seciet influ\nence killed II In the senate? If the\nsenate had linen composed of men\ni lei'leil hy direct vote It would have\n'.ls-e. Ihe l.itlndi. h 1,111; does the\noimt sn.au prefer a senate that\nhas tin- coiirane' tn assassinate a\nrhea.-oiie in the public liiti-ieM to a\nsei.a'e that w.nild he afraid to oppose\nwhat the pie want and Heed\" Mr.\nLIMI.'fl.iil ought to he the last man to\nrep-ou.-h tin hoii.-e with coward! e or\nto commend the senate for cotiri:e.\nSome change must have come over\nbini- posslldv this change may be ex\nplained b slllisi'ilell' acts.\nIn the meantime, the light for the\nelection of sena'orv by a direct vole\nof thn people will continue. Those\nWho behove Hint tile people Should\nthink for themselves anil then elect\nofllrials to carry out their wishes see\nIn the popular ib-dlnn of senators\na iieces-aty step In ihe reform pro\ngram the call way to other reforms\nTHE OKLAHOMA WAY.\nThe following report on an Okla\nhoma hank failure shows the way they\ndo things In that Democratic common\nHealth\n\"Ihe International hank of foul\ngate was repotted to the hank com\nmissioner hy one of his examiners a\nfew days ago or violating the hanking\nlaw of the stale, particularly In Its\nmanaging officers borrowing from the\ndepositors' mom y.\n\"The bank commissioner ni once\nvisited the bank In person and found\nthai the total deposits were about\n:i7.tmn, of which the prefldeut, I.. A.\n('minora, owed over I'LonO, and the\ncashier, 1.. Klzy. owed over $4,0i)0\niu other words, about 30 ier cent, of\nthe deposits had been borrowed by the\ntwo managing olllcers. The bank com\nmissioner demanded that they Itiime\ndlaiely replace the money They\nfailed to do so. He closed the hank\nat 2:1.1 Thursday evening: telephoned\nthe stale banking board: received In\nstructions to linniedlale proceed to\npay all approved deposits In 12 min\nutes from the losing of Ihe bank the\nnank commissioner was ready to pay\napproved deposits. Hy Friday evening\nI'm per cent, of the depositors bad ap\npeared, proved their claims and re\nceived their money. Hy the end of\nthn second day III) per cent, of all de\nposits had been paid. A few desisl\ntora who live in the country don't\nseem to he In any hurry about draw\ning their deposits, due farmer Is re\nported lis answering over the rural\ntelephone that lie Is too busy to come\nafter his money, hut will want It In a\nweek or so.\n\"In tho meantime both the presi\ndent mid tho cashier have been ar\nrested for the violation of the state\nbanking law, and are held under\nheavy bond.\n\"There will probably be no loss to\nthe Btate guaranty fund, and no as\nsessment required on other banks.\nLiquidation will likely reimburse the\nstate fund within 3(1 days. The loss\nwill probably not exceed the capital\nstock.\"\nNoting that a New York Judge has\nenjoined a couple of goats from eating\na cherry tree, the New York Tribune\nremarks that \"Mr. (lumpers may now\ncount on the support of the goats for\nhis antl Injunction bills.\" And Mr.\n(lumpers may also continue to count\non the opposition of other fotir footed\nand longer-eared animals.\nWalter Wellman la confident that\nthe north pole will be discovered some\nday. When It Is the friends of the\ntariff w ill use It as a summer 'resort\nwhile they are engaged In the strenu\nous task of tariff revision.\nThe depoBltors who promptly re\nceived their deposits from that de\nfunct Oklahoma bank are prepared to\noffer convincing proofs that tho guar\nantee of bank deposits Is n most de\nsirable thing.\n\"Once more,\" remarks the Salt I.aka\nHerald, \"we rise to inipil'-e as to tha\nwhereabout of one l.oslle M. Shaw.\"\nGracious, Is the Herald nnahle to ac\ncumulate enough grief without going\nout ana looking for It?\nAmong other amusing things Is the\nspectacle of a Republican congress\nman who dare not call hi congres\nsional soul his own talking about tha\nIncapacity of the Filipinos for self\ngovernment. Congressmen now have private of\nfices, but every two years they hava\nto emerge from the bamb proofi and\ntake, their chances.\nFAIR DEAL NEEDED\nFIRST REQUISITE FOR RETURN\nOF PROSPERITY.\nArtificial Methods of No Avail While\nthe Republican Policy of Protect\ning Trusts and Corporations\nContinues in Force.\nTwo elements are ot work trying to\ncreate prosperity, and both seem to\nen;. main from the same source. Cer\ntain Wall street Interests have been\nforcing up the prlco of securities for\nsome weeks until railroad and Indus\ntrial stocks are higher than before the\npanic occurred Then wo havo thn\nNational Prosperity association going\nup so far as to set June I for tho birth\nof the new prosperity that Is to en\nieop us with a golden mantle. Tho\nplan seems to be to boost stocks In\nWall street so that tlm railroads can\nlioriow tinu'e money, which from the\nHarrlmati-ltockefeller point of view\nis a sine sigti ol prosperity.\nThe maniifai tiiieis are in do their\npart by siartlti up all the factories\n\"li full time anil, ol' course, selling the\npiodinis at full prices\nhei her this hotheil process of pro\ndin-lug prosp' ijl.i '.ill work can, of\ncourse, h\" oaly surmised, hut as thn\nprimal y In at lunii-hed In the slock\nluatk.-t mil n i i mi la 1 1 ii m does not seem\nto have wainnd up the lambs to the\nin Tessa: v i-nt iiii:.ia;'iii. prices are r\nlatin ami Inclined to sag The lambs\nhave I ii -horn too lately and closely\nto b. i xpected to show much l utbii d-a.-m\nuntil tlnir fhecis have had limn\nto grow enough to cover their naked\nness. There Is no doubt that all the tariff\nprotected trusts can start production\nhi a huge scale, hut whether the con\nsumers can pay ihe high prices neces\nsary for this hoi bed brand of pros\nperity Is mine than doubtful. To over\nstock the market with manufactured\ngoods that many people In their pov\nerty through lack of employment can\nnot pay for, will hardly help matters\nunless the trusts are prepared to re\n(luce pries and thus stimulate demand.\nAs the llepiihlhan congress has re\nf'l.nl to reform the tariff, the tarllT\nprotectei trusts still have Ihe power\nto collect their share of the taillT tax:\nand judging from thu action of the\nsteel trust, thu beef trust, the sugar\ntrust and many outers, In determin\ning not to reduce prices, they evident\nly do not intend to divide their pros\nperity with their customers.\nThe people generally must have\nmoney in their pockets before prosper\ni'y returns. Conlldcnco Is a child of\nslow growth, and until confidence Is\nrestored it Is much to be feared that\nprosperity, nourished by the corpora\ntions for their own selfish ends, will\nhardly be deep enough to reach the\nhomes of the people.\nWho has confidence In any pros\nperity for the people from Wall stroet\nmanipulators?\nWho expects prositerity to be pro\nduced by the railroads advancing\nrates?\nCan prosperity come to the people\nby paying the triiHts more than they\ncharge foreigners?\nWho can have any eontldence that\nHepiibllcan Jiollcles will produce pros\nperity since the panic, and with the\nbusiness of the country still at low\nebb?\nA presidential year la not a boom\nyear, and good crops will have to bo\nassured nnd marketed before tho buy\ning power of the people again assures\nprosperity. The boast of tho Repub\nlican politicians that the tariff that\nprotects the trusts assures prosperity\nhaa been rudely shattered during tha\npast yenr, and their do-nothing policy\nduring the session of congress haa not\ncondoned tbnlr evident desire to serve\nthe trusts and corporations more than\nthe people.\nKveryone wanta prosperity, certain\nly for himself, and may be depended\nupon to do what ho can to secure IL\nIf the people can secure a fair deal\nthey will be prospermia, but with the\nRepublican policy of protecting the\ntrusts and corporations In plundering\nthem by high prices and still higher\nrates for transportation, the brand\nof prosperity that has been and Is to\nhe handed out, Is of tho Dcod-sca-ni-ple\nvariety that crumbles at thn touch\nof Investigation. I'loaso keep cool\nnnd give the people a chance to re\ncuperate. I'nder bad laws, and the\nstand pat policy that our Republican\ngovernors have forced us to bear, tho\ngrowth of better times will be alow\nfor the people, though tho trusts and\ncorporations should soon flourish as\nthe green bay tree.\nThe Trusts and High Prices.\nHut If capital and labor arc pursu\ning a right course, It Is not so evident\nthat those trusts which, under tariff\nprotection, can advance the prlcea of\nthe necessaries of life as they see fit,\nare acting In good faith with the con\naiimorB of this country.\nTho trusts obtained their power for\nconsolidating competing concerns with\nthe Implied undorBtnndlng that they\ncould thereby give the people more\nreasonable prices. In tho davs of\ncompetition, after a panic, the cost\nof living was reduced because com\npetitors made prices lower there\nwere no \"gentlemen's agreements.\"\nNow, with trusts wielding an almost\ntyrannical power, tho people find\nprices soaring Instead of being low\nered In depressed times.\nThe farmers cannot he blamed for\nthe exorbitant prices of beef, eggs,\nvegetables and many articles that go\nInto cold storage. They do not re\nceive the fancy prices which the un\nfortunate consumers must pay. The\ntrusts see that no one benefits besides\nthemselves. Boston Globe.\nEXTENSION OF FEDERAL POWER.\nProposed Move Is Directly Opposed to\nthe Constitution.\nThe extension of co'igresslonal antl\npresidential authority in cases of\ndoubtful constitutionality, as suggest\ned by Secretary Root In his nildress\nbefore the conference of governors,\nraises a question of vast Importance to\nthe states and the nation. Tho Root\nIdea Is, aa we understand It, that one\nor more states, having an Interest In\nlegislation by congress not authorized\nby the constitution of tho 1'nlted\nStates, may, through their legislatures,\nask congress to enact such legislation,\nand thereby preclude any Judicial In\nquiry as to tho power of congress in\nthe premises. In other words, the Idea\nIs that particular states may singly or\nIu combination, enter Into treaties\nwith the fednral government, whereby\nthey may obtain special ad vantages\nfrom the latter, without tho concur\nrence of other status.\nThis Idea seems also to have the tip\npiohntlim irf the president, and that of\ncertain governors whose appetite for\na mess of pottage outweighs tlnir re\nspect for tho birthrights of their states.\nNever w as a more insidious suggest Ion\nmade by mortal man\nH Is Interesting to recall some of\nthe provisions of the conslliutlon\nwhich hear upon this subject:\n\"No state shall enter Into any treaty,\nclliance or confederation.\"\n\"No new Btate shall he formed or\nerected wit hi it I he Jurisdiction of an\nother state.\"\nNo state shall bo formed by the\njunction of two or more states, or\nparts of states, without the consent of\nthe legislators thereof, us well as of\ncongress.\"\n\"Three-fourths of the legislatures of\nthe states, or conventions of three\nrourths of the states, as congress shall\nproscribe, may ratify amendments to\nthe constitution.\"\n\"When the choice of a president\nshall be devolved upon (he house of\nleptoscntallves, the vole shall be taken\nby states.\"\nNow, suppose those states which are\neager for an appropriation from con\ngress for Ihe establishment of the Ap\npalachlan forest reserve at the expense\nof their neighbors, should each invite\ncongress to pass such a law as It de\nsires on that subject, though more\nthan three fourths of the states should\noppose It; nnd suppose five or six\nslates should combine or confederate,\nwith a view to securing such legisla\ntion, and should agree that In case the\nelection of a president were thrown\ninto the house of representatives, their\nrepresentatives should vote as a unit\nfor the candidate of that r.ntional party\nwhich should agree to enact such leg\nislation In splto of all constitutional\nlimitations would not this amount to\na revolution? Is there no ground for\nBiispectlng that the insidious sugges\ntion of Mr. Root was made In view of\nthe poBBf hlllty that the election of a\npresident may, as a result of the ueit\ncampaign, be thrown Into the house of\nrepresentatives.? To bribe those\nstutes which huvc a deep special Inter\nest In waterways, forest reserves and\nconservation of certain national re\nsources, at the expense of other stutes,\nwould be tho surest method of destroy\ning the federal constitution nnd set\nting up without fear of successful re\nsistance an absolute central govern\nment nt Washington. Is It not pos\nsible that this end Is concealed be\nhind the means proposed? Why should\nanyone suggest unconstitutional and\nrevolutionary means, unless he has un\nconstitutional and revolutionary ends\nIn view?\nIn the fifth article of the constitu\ntion, a method Is prescribed for ex\ntending or curtailing tho limits of\nfederal authority; and heretofore that\nmothod has boon pursued. Any devia\ntion from It now would be quite as un\njustifiable and far more dangerous\nthan over before. For It seems that\neven tho governors of some of the\nsouthern states, where states' rights\nhave had their citadel from the be\nginning, are willing to play the role\nof Esau.\nRepublican Extravagance.\nIn the first ton months of the cur\nrent fiscal year tho revenues declined\nonly $11,000,000, which Is fnr loss than\nlast year's surplus to date, while tho\nexpenditures Increased by JJt!6,000,000.\nThe government can pay ns It goes\nand have a big pllo ahead nt tho end\nof tho year, but no resources, and no\nthrift on the part of the peoplo can\nstand tho drain which tho Republican\ncongress Is making on both. 8L\nLouis Republic.\nTho Sixtieth congress at Its first\nsession has appropriated moro money\nthan any of Its predecessors. It has\nmade appropriations which It knows\ntho revenues will not cover. Outside\nof this field of activity It hns been the\npre-eminent \"do-nothing\" congress.\nIn passing the billion mark the ap\npropriations under tho Cannon rules\ngo $88,000,000 above the highest pre\nvious Republican record. Hut what's\n$88,000,000 among friends of the Can\nnon rules whon othor people pay the\nmoney?\nRepublican members of the house\nwho began by opposing the Aldrlch\nVreeland makeshift and were con\nverted by Mr. fljieakcr Cannon's pork\nbar'! will now have plenty of oppor\ntunities to explain It all to their con\nstituents. 8hlp Subsidy.\nThe ship subsidy amendment to the\npost office appropriation bill was de\nfeated In the house by a vote of 154\nnays to 14S yeas; the Democrats vot\ning Boltdly agatnBt It. It will come\nup again after the election: and un\nless the Democrats win. It will become\na law. It Is favored by the Hearstltes\nand the Republicans.\nHow It Works. I\nOnce there was a struggling young\nauthor who was blest with many\nfriends, all of whom told him that h\nwas tho coming gn-ut writer of th\ncountry.\nSo one day a bright thought struck\nblm. He said:\n\"I will publish my book, and all my j\nfriends who admire It so much will buy\nmy book, and I will be rich.\"\nSo be printed his book.\nAnd all of his friends waited for j\nhim to send them autographed copies\nof his hook. i\nAnd so his books were sold as Junk.\nAnd ever after he didn't havo any\nfriends. Success.\nTry Murine Eye Remedy\nFor Red, Weak, Weary, Watery Eyn.\nMurine Doenn't Snuirt hoodies Eye l'mn.\nAll DriiKKitts Si ll Marine at 50ct. The 4B\nPago Hook in each I'kg. is worth Dollart\nin evrrv home. Read it. We will Mad all\nour Eye Hi. ok\" Free Write us to-day.\nAnV your !rugirtt.\nMurine Eye Remedy Co., Chicago,\nSimple.\nMrs. Chlnner I can't understand\nwhy your daughter Jilted a rich man\nto marry a poor one.\nMrs. Chatter It's very simple, my\nyear. With the one she would have\nhad everything to lose, but with the I\nother she has everything to gain St.\nLouis Dispatch.\nFIT t Vltm' panr anil N.rr..'H P1n-l pr-\nnutiiffitlf.-ur.-l tiv lir K:nii' ori-.it N.rv.. Ufsl.,rr.\nHiui.l f..r HIKK t\" to tciil li..tt I., iiml tr...itis... lir.\nH. 11. Klinu, M.. '.i Arcli sural, l'I..U.Ir.'li 1'a.\nGood manners are the blossoms ol\ngood sense, and, It may be added,\ngood feeling, too. Locke.\nM-cf H 'hV'M TO\ndenier or I.ewi J-jctory, rt-una. 111.\nThe greater the difficulty, the great\ner the glory In surmouii'.lng It. FJpl\neurus. Mra. Wlnllow'a Nimthtna Hjmp,\nYnr chllitrBD mrUltuir, Mflru. Itm sural, rrilui-M\nttftffltDftUun.auayii'ala.curM wiodculki. Ktatwtua.\nMore peoplo are fooled by the truth\nthan by lies.\nUOIW\nBACKACH\nThe back is the mainspring of\nwoman's orgnnism. It quiokly calls\nattention to trouble Yij aching-. It\ntells, with other symptoms, such aa\nnervousness, headache, puins in the\nloins, weight in tho lower port of\nthe body, that a woman's feminine\norganism needs immediatcattention.\nIn such cases the one sure remedy\nwhich speedily removes the cause,\nand restores the feminine organism\nto healthy, normal Condition is\nLYDIA E.PINKHAM'S\nVEGETABLE COMPOUND\nMrs. Will Young, of 6 Columbia\nAve., Rockland, Me., says\nI was troubled for along time with\ndreadful backaches and a pai